Koko Taylor (born Cora Anna Walton, September 28, 1928 – June 3, 2009) was an American singer whose style encompassed Chicago blues, electric blues, rhythm and blues and soul blues.
Sometimes called "The Queen of the Blues", she was known for her rough, powerful vocals.
She was spotted by Willie Dixon in 1962, and this led to more opportunities for performing and her first recordings.

In 1964 Dixon brought Taylor to Checker Records, a subsidiary label of Chess Records, for which she recorded "Wang Dang Doodle", a song written by Dixon and recorded by Howlin' Wolf five years earlier.

Koko Taylor (born Cora Anna Walton, September 28, 1928 – June 3, 2009) was an American singer whose style encompassed Chicago blues, electric blues, rhythm and blues and soul blues.
Born on a farm near Memphis, Tennessee, Taylor was the daughter of a sharecropper.
She left Tennessee for Chicago in 1952 with her husband, Robert "Pops" Taylor, a truck driver.
She left Tennessee for Chicago in 1952 with her husband, Robert "Pops" Taylor, a truck driver.
In the late 1950s, she began singing in blues clubs in Chicago.
In 1963 she had a single on USA Records, and in 1964 a cut on a Chicago blues collection on Spivey Records, called Chicago Blues.

Taylor became better known by touring in the United States in the late 1960s and early 1970s, and she became accessible to a wider record-buying public when she signed a recording contract with Alligator Records in 1975.
